			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1631">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>In her essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/249/">Adrift</a>&rdquo; [March 2006], Suzanne Murray eloquently expressed the numbness, isolation, and grief I felt after my own father&rsquo;s death. Amidst the compassionate outpouring of sympathy from close friends and family, I sensed a subtle but increasing pressure to &ldquo;get over it.&rdquo; Her essay not only confirms the fact that each person&rsquo;s grief is unique, but also speaks to how the natural world has a power to heal that goes beyond societal comforts and becomes almost miraculous.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Annette Udall<br>Newcastle, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="1603">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Suzanne Murray&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/249">Adrift</a>&rdquo; [March 2006] touched something deep inside me. After I read it, I cried silently as I rode the train on a sunny spring morning.</p>

<p>I agree that our culture tries to hide from grief. I lost my own dad to cancer when I was eight and don&rsquo;t have many memories of him. The father Murray describes, who laughed, who experimented, who taught, whose spirit was evident even behind the stern veneer &mdash; I&rsquo;ve never known my own father that way.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Matt Crichton<br>Boston, Massachusetts</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
